## Level 27 → Level 28
**Objective:** Clone a git repository hosted on the bandit server
and find the password inside it.

**Commands Used:**
```bash
git clone ssh://bandit27-git@bandit.labs.overthewire.org:2220/home/bandit27-git/repo
                                        # cloned the remote repository
                                        # entered bandit27 password when prompted
cd repo                                 # moved into cloned repository
ls -la                                  # found README file
cat README                              # revealed the password
```

**What is Git?**
- Git is a version control system — tracks changes to files over time
- Allows multiple people to collaborate on the same codebase
- Stores entire history of a project including all previous versions
- Used by almost every software project in the world
- GitHub, GitLab, and Bitbucket are platforms that host git repositories

**What is a Repository (repo)?**
- A folder that git tracks — contains all project files and history
- Can be stored locally on your machine or remotely on a server
- `git clone` downloads a remote repository to your local machine
- Once cloned you have a full copy of the repo and its history

**Git Clone URL Breakdown:**
```
git clone ssh://bandit27-git@bandit.labs.overthewire.org:2220/home/bandit27-git/repo
           │    │            │                            │    │
           │    │            │                            │    └── Path to repo
           │    │            │                            └── Port number
           │    │            └── Host
           │    └── Username
           └── Protocol (SSH)
```

**Why Port Goes in the URL:**
- Normal git clone: `git clone ssh://user@host/path`
- With custom port: `git clone ssh://user@host:port/path`
- Unlike SSH where `-p` flag sets the port, git clone requires
  the port inside the URL after the host with a `:`
- Using `-p` with git clone doesn't work — common mistake

**What I Learned:**
- Git repositories can be hosted on SSH servers
- `git clone` downloads an entire repository to your local machine
- Port number goes inside the SSH URL for git, not as a `-p` flag
- Repositories often contain sensitive files left by developers —
  README files, config files, credentials etc
- Always explore a cloned repo thoroughly with `ls -la`

**Real Pentesting Relevance:**
Finding exposed git repositories is a very common real world
vulnerability. Developers often accidentally commit sensitive data:
- Passwords and API keys in config files
- Private keys in repository history
- Internal infrastructure details in README files
- Even deleted files can be recovered from git history

**Key Takeaway:**
Git repositories are treasure troves in pentesting. Even if
sensitive data has been deleted from the latest version, it
may still exist in the commit history. Always check:
- Current files with `ls -la`
- Git history with `git log`
- Previous versions with `git show`
- All branches with `git branch -a`
